[2026-03-18T18:32:47Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017zBvzCBx4FYoPphcV1EM93","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche System Design\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→Cloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\n     6→environments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\n     7→agentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n     8→\n     9→This document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n    10→\n    11→## System Components\n    12→\n    13→Cloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→cmd/\n    17→  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n    18→  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n    19→  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→### cloche (CLI)\n    23→\n    24→Short-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n    25→\n    26→Subcommands:\n    27→- `run <workflow>` — Launch a new workflow run\n    28→- `resume <run-id> [step]` — Resume a failed run from a specific step (or first failed step)\n    29→- `status [run-id]` — Check run status\n    30→- `logs <run-id>` — Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n    31→- `stop <run-id>` — Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n    32→\n    33→Accepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n    34→\n    35→### cloched (Daemon)\n    36→\n    37→Long-running process. Responsibilities:\n    38→- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n    39→- Listen to status streams from running agents\n    40→- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n    41→- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n    42→- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n    43→\n    44→The daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\n    45→and collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n    46→\n    47→### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n    48→\n    49→Autonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n    50→- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n    51→- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n    52→- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n    53→- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n    54→- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n    55→\n    56→The agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n    57→\n    58→## Communication\n    59→\n    60→### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n    61→\n    62→- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n    63→- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n    64→- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n    65→\n    66→### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n    67→\n    68→- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n    69→- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n    70→- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n    71→- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n    72→\n    73→## Workflow DSL\n    74→\n    75→### Vocabulary\n    76→\n    77→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    78→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    79→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    80→| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b35c7e72-315f-476b-a926-30b8621f3c48","uuid":"406ee038-ca06-4d9e-a1ac-826255a7a4c1","timestamp":"2026-03-18T18:32:35.825Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-02-20-cloche-system-design.md","content":"# Cloche System Design\n\n## Overview\n\nCloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\nenvironments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\nagentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n\nThis document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n\n## System Components\n\nCloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n\n```\ncmd/\n  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n```\n\n### cloche (CLI)\n\nShort-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n\nSubcommands:\n- `run <workflow>` — Launch a new workflow run\n- `resume <run-id> [step]` — Resume a failed run from a specific step (or first failed step)\n- `status [run-id]` — Check run status\n- `logs <run-id>` — Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n- `stop <run-id>` — Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n\nAccepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n\n### cloched (Daemon)\n\nLong-running process. Responsibilities:\n- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n- Listen to status streams from running agents\n- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n\nThe daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\nand collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n\n### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n\nAutonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n\nThe agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n\n## Communication\n\n### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n\n- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n\n### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n\n- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n\n## Workflow DSL\n\n### Vocabulary\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |","numLines":80,"startLine":1,"totalLines":253}}}
